Way before the Surrealists were splashing dreamy colors onto canvas, Henri Rousseau was busy crafting his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. His 1910 painting, The Dream, is a masterclass in his personal aspirations and internal tug-of-war. On one hand, he yearned for acceptance, recognition, and praise from fellow artists and art enthusiasts. On the other hand, he struggled with whether to conform to established painting styles or forge his own path. The Dream encapsulates this lifelong conflict.

To truly grasp the significance of The Dream, let's first delve a bit into Rousseau's life. Born in Laval, northwest France, on May 21, 1844, Rousseau didn't have much formal art training. Instead, he worked as a gabelou, or municipal toll service employee, until the age of forty. Despite his plain circumstances, he dreamt of a new life through painting, offering solace after the tragedies of his first wife's and eight infant children's deaths. Unlike his peers, who romanticized peasants in their art, Rousseau remained a folk painter, reflecting the hopes and dreams of the average citizen.

Rousseau’s desire for acceptance was understandable given his situation. He started his artistic journey late and in the shadow of many renowned artists. He only began to gain recognition around the time Matisse was building his reputation. Jan Gordon in Modern French Painters notes that while both artists competed in the art world, their motivations were different. Matisse sought to paint unconventionally to avoid clichés, while Rousseau aimed to paint conventionally to be accepted by the Artiste Français (92).

Many a great philosopher has pondered the deep connection between ethics and aesthetics. I believe this is because the essence of both lies in something ineffable. As John Keats put it in his famous "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty — That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." While we often learn about ethics and aesthetics through education and experience, our appreciation of them seems to come naturally. Ethics and aesthetics, you see, are not about prescribing rules, but rather trying to understand why something is moral or beautiful. We grapple with the intricacies of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, talking about elements like contrast and cultural context, but in the end, the true reason behind its beauty eludes us. It's often that intangible "something" that makes us appreciate a piece of art or literature. This je ne sais quoi is what makes art and morality so powerful, and it's this transcendental nature that binds them together.

We experience both ethics and aesthetics at a deep, almost mystical level, a place where we can feel them but not entirely explain them. This is especially true of literature's moral quality, as McKean suggests. He notes that, unlike other arts like music, literature is uniquely tied to our moral lives because it reflects the values we hold dear. This moral quality is why literature is so important to us, and why ethics and aesthetics are so closely intertwined.

Germany today stands as a mighty nation, its unique culture stretching from the alpine peaks of München to the Baltic shores of Kiel. This blend can be felt along the Rhine in Köln, through the heart of Germany, and into the Elbe Valley in Dresden. Given this diverse culture, it's not surprising that Germany, as we know it, is a fusion of various sources and tribes.

Germania, the ancestral home of the Germans, has a name with uncertain origins. Some scholars believe it came from the Germanic Tribe known as the Tungrians, who were later called Germans. Others think it might be derived from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout," suggesting loud or noisy people. Tacitus, in his work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," written in AD 98, describes the Germans as aboriginal and not intermingled with other races. He notes that no one would choose to leave the comforts of Rome for the harsh lands of Germania, unless it was their home. The Romans, while sending out expeditions to trade and conquer, mostly returned to their empire. This led to the Germanic tribes residing on the empire's borders, trading goods and skills, and sometimes serving in the Roman army.

I stood there, staring down at the view in front of me, my mind blank like a canvas awaiting inspiration. Unemotionally, silently, I observed the picture before me, my practiced awareness taking it all in but refusing to connect it to any abstract idea. Thoughts flowed in and out of my mind so quickly, it was as if I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and fluid experience of what I was seeing. Once, an artist I'd worked with suggested I buy a book called 'The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain'. I'd been wanting to learn to draw since I was six, and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to how the brain interprets lines. One of the techniques it teaches is to place a square frame around any picture you want to study, turning a complex scene into a simple one. At the time, I couldn't quite mentally project that artist's frame. I was too overwhelmed, too awestruck to do anything but stand and gaze in wonderment. Picasso's blue phase, Monet's love for greenery, the Italian Renaissance masters' vibrant colors - if I had any artistic pretensions, here was where my picture began, my story started, 'Work in Brown'.

My hand touched the handle of my chosen tool, muscles tensing and relaxing as I guided it through space, my mind's will taking shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Pieces of matter broke away and were carried away to nothingness. But the second time, my hand smacked the handle of the toilet with more urgency. The offensive brown package just wouldn't budge, stuck like a slug on the toilet's bottom. I stood there, a mop in hand, feet set a foot apart, a green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat. I frowned, staring at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the bathroom cleaners at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more quiet moments to myself, and then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the end of the toilet paper, and began to wrap itself around and around like an oven mitt. Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

So another month has gone by, and of course, my life is pretty much the same old thing. Not much happened, except for the usual stuff. I've been thinking about teen drivers and the alarming rates of fatal accidents among them. The National Institutes of Health say that a part of the problem is that their brains just aren't ready for the risks of driving. Plus, they're just inexperienced, which leads to more crashes, rollovers, speeding, and driving off-road. And if you think it's bad when they're alone, it's even worse when they drive with their peers. A study from the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center shows that the more passengers there are, the more accidents happen.

States have tried to make teens safer by putting restrictions on their licenses, like only letting them drive during certain hours and not with other minors. But these are just temporary fixes. The real problem is that teens, as a group, aren't ready to handle the responsibilities of driving. Even psychologist Marvin Zuckerman says 18 is too young. He's done research showing that teens under 19-20 love to take risks just for the thrill of it. So, we should delay driving until this urge starts to fade. If we don't, we'll see more accidents and the death toll could get way worse. By 2010, the younger Baby Boomers will be driving, and millions of new teen drivers will hit the road.

Legislation could be simple. Schools could teach driving basics, but no one under 18 could drive. A permit could still be issued, but a certain number of practical training hours would be required, like the 6 hours behind the wheel and 50 hours with an adult that California requires. Since the problem affects teens across the nation, uniform national legislation would be a reasonable and effective solution. This idea isn't new, but it could really make a difference.

So I decided to dive into the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, specifically looking at the fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films were known for their creative editing, which often created illusions. My focus in studying these films was to describe the poetic elements they used, particularly in the majority of trick films, and to explore the unique characteristics of a few later films. Most of these early trick films were bound to a set within a frontal proscenium, with no camera movement, relying on long and medium shots, and adhering to the one shot = one film approach. However, there were a few films at the start of the twentieth century that dared to break these rules by introducing multiple shots.

One thing these trick films share is that they were often filmed in an interior set, with the camera fixed in a frontal proscenium position. This was common in early films, taking inspiration from the theatre and vaudeville performances. The limitation of this approach was that figures in the films only moved side-to-side and didn't walk towards or away from the camera. For example, in the film "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), actors entered from the right side and moved back and forth along the horizontal axis, without the camera following them.

Another commonality was the use of long and medium shots, with close-ups never being used. This style was taken from theatre and vaudeville traditions, where the audience saw the entire performance within the stage's borders. Actors didn't move towards the camera, so close-ups weren't used.

Most of these early trick films followed the pattern of one conceptual shot equaling one film, which kept their length to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second. This also limited their use in storytelling, focusing more on short vaudeville-style tricks. However, in trick films, one conceptual shot didn't equate to one physical shot. A single “shot” could actually be several joined together to create illusions of apparition or disappearance. For instance, in "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), a closer look reveals that the physical shot with Mary’s severed "head" begins, even though the film is conceptually one shot in the viewer's eyes.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate for Republicanism. Although primarily an agriculturalist, his career in politics instilled in him a strong commitment to personal freedom and government, making him vocal on these matters. His dedication to an agrarian system shaped his views on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

Taylor believed the United States had a unique chance to establish an ideal system, as there was no native tradition to obstruct the government's creation. He held strong convictions about the natural rights of man, which he thought were interdependent, meaning if one was denied, all would fail, and the value of what remained would be diminished. These rights, in his view, should be beyond the government's reach.

To create this ideal society, Taylor thought a government must account for the inherent good and evil within people. He was firm in his dualistic morality, claiming, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human." He defined good principles as those that protected private property, improved agriculture, and discouraged capitalism. A government founded on these principles would function equitably, he believed, regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be driven by avarice and self-interest. He saw self-interest as a natural trait that only became evil when it led to the creation of sub-societies at the expense of others. A good government would retain man's natural evil but must be carefully watched to prevent the addition of bad principles.

Like many of his contemporaries, Taylor advocated for a strict construction of the Constitution, calling for an extremely limited Federal government with only the rights and powers explicitly stated in the Constitution. He understood that an extensive Federal government could be expensive and despotic, but he also believed a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous. Without considering the intent of the writers, it could easily become corrupt. Moreover, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly described the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

So, referring back to Figure 17, we saw a noticeable drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of our project. It was somewhat disheartening, and it's tricky to pinpoint the exact cause. The onset of winter in New England means fewer people commute by bike or on foot, which could account for some of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester, when everyone is busy wrapping up schoolwork and grades. The commuter log might have just slipped off their radar. Additionally, the holiday season can take a toll, with a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many don't need to come to campus. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which might also contribute to the low log submissions for that month. However, none of this really explains the low February numbers. It's also possible that any project like this experiences an initial burst of excitement that naturally tapers off. To combat this, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which did increase log submissions for that month. So one of the challenges we faced was maintaining project momentum despite these natural decreases and the holidays/semester breaks inherent in higher education.

Another challenge is the deeply ingrained culture of driving cars. People value the freedom, independence, and flexibility it provides. Thus, it's crucial to provide compelling incentives for alternative commuting. We handed out gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, an independent bookstore, and even some national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see if larger prizes like a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car could boost participation. The nature of the prizes didn't change throughout the project, but perhaps varying the value over time could have helped. The gift cards seemed sufficient at the start, but if we had announced additional bigger prizes in December and January, like bicycles and hybrid/electric cars, participation might have increased instead of decreasing.

So, ETFs, or exchange-traded funds, are like securities that aim to mirror an index, a commodity, or a collection of assets, but trade on exchanges like stocks. They offer the benefits of diversification, like index funds, plus the perks of single stock ownership, such as short selling, margin buying, and purchasing shares in any quantity. While these advantages are appealing, ETFs have costs just like mutual funds, with the added expense of trade commissions. One of the best things about ETFs is the wide variety of choices. However, it's always wise for investors to assess whether these claimed benefits, like diversification, truly exist and how significantly they impact performance. Let's dive into the ETF IHF and compare it with its top 10 holdings to see if owning one ETF is as beneficial as owning a diversified portfolio of these ten stocks.

For simplicity, we'll only consider the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF. Here they are:

To gauge how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF, we'll use their current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate their contributions to portfolio Beta and Return. The results are as follows:

From the chart, it's clear that a portfolio of just the top ten holdings offers a 6.11% higher return than the ETF, a 16% boost, with a lower Beta of 0.12. It seems that a portfolio of these top ten stocks could provide better returns with less risk. However, we need to check if the means of these two portfolios are statistically different.

To determine this, we'll examine the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks, normalized to 100%, and compare their total standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

So, Edgar Allan Poe had this poem called "Dream-Land," which he considered one of his better works. In this piece, Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, a reference traced back to Virgil. Virgil mentioned Thulé in his writings, describing it as an island north of Britain, marking the edge of the known world for the Greeks. While Virgil did use the term, there's a more recent source that Poe might have been influenced by: Goethe.

This connection is important because it shows Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writing. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," pointed out the similarities between Poe's and Goethe's poems, suggesting that Poe was likely emulating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a renowned writer of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts: the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. Within the second part of Faust, there's a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem tells the story of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. After her passing, he becomes consumed by grief and drinking, eventually deciding to end his life. He gives his possessions to his children, keeps the goblet, walks to a cliff, throws it into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies.

The king in "The King of Thule" and the speaker in "Dream-Land" share striking similarities, mirroring a dark doppelganger of Poe's loss and his drinking habit. The romantic drama based on Faust, created by H. P. Grattan in 1842, was published just a year before Poe's use of the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe references Thule twice in his collected works. He uses "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and in "Dream-Land," using the term as bookends for the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark, lonely, and haunted by dead friends, seeing a shaded world without color. These scenes echo the themes from "The King of Thule," where the king is overcome with grief, loneliness, and a loss of will to live.

Goethe was a notable author whom Poe would have known, not just for his connection to Tennyson but also because of the many reproductions of his work following the original publications.

So under California law, let's break it down. Could a customer injured from slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store get punitive damages by proving the store manager acted with malice? Maybe. To make this case stick, the customer, Jennifer Palmer, would need to show that the manager, Paul Martin, was aware of the risk of harm and still chose to ignore it. She can point out that multiple previous incidents occurred due to unaddressed spills and that Martin knew this. His actions, such as not cleaning the spill while he was eating, could be seen as despicable, but less so than the fact that he ignored repeated requests to clean up. The judge is unlikely to dismiss her case outright, but it might face challenges in proving that Martin's actions were truly malicious and not just negligent.

On that fateful day, October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee alerted Martin about the applesauce spill, but he was on a dinner break and didn't want to deal with it. Another employee tried again at 5:15 pm, but Martin gave the same response. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell, resulting in a serious back injury. Palmer is now suing for damages, and we are considering whether to file a motion to dismiss part of her claim. To recover punitive damages in California, one must show the defendant acted with oppression, fraud, or malice. For malice, conduct must have been intended to cause harm or, if not intended, it must be despicable and committed with a willful disregard for others' rights. The judge might find that Martin's actions were maliciously indifferent to the safety of others, but this claim might be tough to prove.

Well, almost four years back, I took a course on Islam over at CBC. One of the major points of contention in that class was the question of whether or not Islam is inherently hostile. Funny thing is, I think that debate's even more pertinent today than it was then. Looking back on the world since 9/11, I've noticed a shift in the mass media's stance on Islam and extremists—from outright hostility to a near-worshipping tolerance. I mean, can you imagine, in 2001, having a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with his clear Muslim roots?

The biography of the Prophet Muhammad has always intrigued me. The more I've learned about his history, the more I'm struck by how his life doesn't quite match the image portrayed in the biography. From what I've known and studied before, I always thought Muhammad was the type to use force to convert people to Islam—conquering tribes and imposing his religion on them. But according to the biography, he's written as a sort of martyr, misunderstood and humbled. It's like, one by one, people started seeking him out. Huh, that's quite different from my previous understanding.

There are some uncanny similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the ‘miracles’ of Muhammad. The most notable one is the multiplication of mutton and milk to feed forty men. This style of storytelling makes me believe they were trying to elevate Muhammad to this humble, truth-living prophet who didn't need to prove his points through miracles. It's like they're stealing Jesus's thunder, making Muhammad seem like a basically perfect, Christ-like figure. That rubs me the wrong way.

There are also a lot of stories in the biography that seem to serve as some sort of proof of 'witnesses' converting to Islam on their own. Trouble is, these stories often come from third-party sources—like, "So-and-so heard from this person who heard from that person." I don't like this because, while their intention might be to validate the stories through hearsay, it just makes the stories seem even more dubious.

The thing that bugs me the most is how they try to portray Muhammad as this godly, humble, endearing, and wise figure. History, however, tells a different story. It's like they're trying to whitewash Muhammad's rise to power. I can't help but think if Muslims today are aware of the real history behind their prophet.

Well, the teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his lifetime were quickly forgotten when Christianity began to develop beyond his life. If we look at the big picture, Christianity seems to have been drifting farther and farther from its roots. Today's world shows a growing trend of progressive thinking, but tradition-holding individuals may not be enough to steer the whole. Among Christians, a deeper historical understanding will grow in the coming years. There will be a longing to distinguish the doctrines added to Christianity over time from the original intentions of its founder. This process may take decades or even centuries, but it's inevitable: Christianity will revert to its original form. A movement will emerge, peeling away layers of doctrine, like rewinding time, until only Jesus' original message remains. When this trend reaches the United States and Europe, it will influence many to worship as if they're living during Jesus' time, following only his ideas. The church will remain strong, leading the way, but the diversity of beliefs and practices will lessen, with similarities replacing differences among regions, denominations, and divisions. History is full of reversals. For instance, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire but later, the empire itself became Christian. Our country has seen African-American slavery turn into African-American leadership. The future of Christianity will follow this pattern, undoing history to find its source and reducing diversity. A vital part of this process will be interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, not literally. So, what has changed since Jesus' time?

I hold that "The Jungle" reveals how at our core, humans are inherently greedy and selfish. Our chief concern is to make our own lives as comfortable and prosperous as possible, but we pay no heed to those beneath us. The novel illustrates this through the factory owners and managers who are solely focused on expanding their empires. They are unmoved by the harm caused by their operations, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world," a vivid description of the environmental devastation. They show no concern for the workers or the animals who suffer due to the factories' emissions and waste. The owners' sole goal is profit, exemplified by their exploitation of employees: "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They push workers to their limits, laying off mass numbers without notice or compensation. In that period, few laws or protections existed for workers, allowing managers to run rampant. The book suggests that those who perished in Packingtown were expected to endure the miserable conditions without aid or escape. Organizations to assist workers were scarce, and unions often exacerbated the plight of the workers by lining their pockets at the workers' expense. The workers were trapped in a system that treated them like slaves, as "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers."

Many authors employ various techniques to evoke specific feelings or perspectives in their readers regarding important subjects. Some techniques work better than others. In his novel The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald uses several of these methods. Often, he couples adjectives and nouns in unusual ways to create a certain atmosphere around a subject. Alternatively, he assigns meaning to symbols and then utilizes them for this purpose. Fitzgerald employs this latter technique with numerous colors, such as gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald constructs a particular significance for white/gray and red/pink colors, which he later employs to engender specific associations with significant subjects.

The meaning Fitzgerald assigns to white/gray is uniformity, with white symbolizing a higher social status and gray denoting older, faded elements. This is evident early in the novel, as characters are frequently depicted in white. Daisy and Jordan are consistently described as “in white” (8), and even Nick wears “white flannels” (41) at Gatsby’s party. Only when Nick describes Gatsby’s party does he mention other colors, such as “gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald reinforces this association by coloring everyday subjects in white/gray. For instance, Nick’s work commute is described as “down the white chasms of lower New York” (56), and people’s names at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61) on his schedule. Furthermore, common or unimportant characters and places are often associated with white or gray. For example, Jordan and Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, and there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of ashes. Similarly, the “Italian child” on the train is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is a “gray old man” (27).

Later, Fitzgerald uses these colors to convey a sense of uniformity or unimportance around significant subjects, particularly through his portrayal of Daisy. After a prolonged period without notable mentions of either color, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as “dressed in white” in a “little white roadster,” making her seem less like a character and more like a mere addition to Gatsby’s pursuits (74). He further uses this technique to depict Daisy as a uniform addition, for example, with a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County, with its mild and sunny climate, is a hotspot for agriculture. Tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers are common crops. The demand for organic, community-supported agriculture is substantial, with many local organizations boasting long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also quite popular. Some organic farms offer tours of their operations and provide opportunities for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This setup allows landowners to benefit from government programs while also enhancing habitat, offering recreational use, and generating income through tours and educational programs.

Culture, it's a thing that's crucial in any negotiation. It's not just a single, uniform thing, but it's made up of what it isn't and what it stands for too. It's not all the same everywhere, and it's not a static thing either. So saying things like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" is too broad. It's better to understand how the culture of the people you're dealing with affects the negotiation, especially if you're from a different culture. When you're dealing with a foreign culture, you'll naturally compare it to your own, but that's okay. Understanding a culture involves more than just learning its history, it's about understanding its prejudices too. Instead of judging or trying to change them, you just need to accept them and work within their boundaries, especially if you're at a disadvantage in the negotiation. If you're on "home turf," respecting their traditions and beliefs can help you get past any cultural barriers and move things forward.

Culture isn't just about national or international differences. Even within the same country, companies can have their own unique cultures. For example, some companies might emphasize long hours, while others might have a more relaxed schedule. You can see these differences in things like employee dress codes, how they communicate, and how they hire people. Some companies encourage philanthropy at all levels, while others only do it through "company approved" charities. Just look at American corporate culture to see how diverse it is. Even within a single company, there can be different cultures based on location or environment. Some cultures may seem more uniform, but that's just the surface. You need to look deeper to understand them.

Values are key because they tell you why a culture is the way it is. If saving face or communal harmony is important, a negotiator won't publicly humiliate their company or their boss to win. Likewise, if a negotiator comes from a culture that favors tough bargaining, they won't rush to settle early. Understanding these generalities before the negotiation is important, but it's also good to know something about your opponent on a personal level to make the negotiation more effective.

So the fool in his heart once proclaimed, "There is no God." This notion is first seen in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and also stands at the center of St. Anselm’s argument for God's existence. This view is also echoed by another author we'll discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Since both arguments are aimed at proving the same divine entity, specifically the God of the Bible, let's start by assuming they are both correct in their belief. To compare their arguments effectively, we must assume they are discussing the same God. So, while each of them offers valid points, neither presents a comprehensive basis for belief in God.

St. Anselm’s approach begins with faith, emphasizing that understanding God requires looking within oneself. He argues that since God exists within our minds, we cannot imagine his nonexistence. This idea, while somewhat complicated, posits that proof of God's existence lies within our own consciousness. St. Anselm suggests we don't need external evidence to find truth about God; it's inherently within our minds. This is often referred to as faith in Christian teachings.

Thomas Aquinas, however, takes a different stance. He believes God's existence can be proven through reason and empirical evidence, without needing faith. This argument is advantageous for evangelism, as it can persuade converts without relying on their willingness to accept unprovable faith. St. Thomas presents five logical arguments to support his claim: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument demonstrates that the need for God is logically necessary, even without direct observation.

In essence, Aquinas argues that logical deductions can prove God's existence, much like knowing a missing puzzle piece's features without seeing it.

Long ago, around the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would later be known as Buddha was born. Throughout his life, he abandoned the world and achieved enlightenment, giving birth to the teachings that would become Buddhism, with its most traditional branch being known as Theravada Buddhism. This religion has been around for about 2500 years, and it has evolved significantly since Buddha's time. You can see these changes in various places, such as in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where an annual water-cutting ceremony is celebrated. Monks and laypeople alike participate in this event, which has some religious significance, even though Buddha never taught about such a festivity.

The changes in Buddhism over time can be seen in both its superficial traditions and its core beliefs. The Theravada Buddhist community, whether from a monastic or lay perspective, has had to adjust its doctrinal principles over the years due to both internal and external factors, as well as hostile and benign influences. To better understand this discussion, let's define some key terms. Internal forces refer to influences coming from within the Buddhist community, regardless of one's status, while external forces refer to influences from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces are any that aim to harm or damage the Buddhist community, often stemming from negative perceptions of Buddhism. Benign forces, on the other hand, do not intend to harm or help the community but may do so indirectly.

To delve into the basics of Theravada Buddhism, we must first explore its core doctrinal principles. Buddhists seek refuge in the Triple Gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka includes the metaphysical components of Buddhism, such as Anatta (no self), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence of all things). By recognizing these concepts, one can escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, and along with it, lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion), ultimately achieving enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka sets rules for life, with laypeople following five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances), while monks follow many more disciplinary rules. The fundamental doctrine in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths: first, that life is suffering (Dukkha); second, that attachment is the cause of suffering; third, that suffering can be overcome; and fourth, the path to the end of suffering.

So, let me tell you a story about two nations, the United States of America and Mexico. They had a long-standing rivalry that lasted for a whopping 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the U.S. attacked and conquered Mexico, gaining Texas and the American Southwest as new territory. There were many other skirmishes between them, which finally softened just before the First World War.

Their rivalry started over key issues like religion, culture, and tradition, with a significant clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31). It's not unlike many other nations that have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor; nations sharing a border often have conflicting interests, leading to rivalries. The U.S. and Mexico are no different. David M. Pletcher (1977) put it this way, “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).

Religious differences were a huge rift between them, similar to many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) stated, “if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy” (p.86). This ideological struggle was not about political structure but religious preferences. The distrust between the United States and Mexico stemmed from the distrust between the English and Spanish, which was passed down from their colonial rulers. This lingering mistrust made it difficult to establish friendly foreign relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) listed 17 disputes between Mexico and the U.S. during their 57-year rivalry. Most of these disputes were about territorial issues, like border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American border towns were a significant issue that persisted until both nations used military force to secure their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) noted that the rivalry began to ease as Mexico became highly dependent on the United States, and it finally ended when American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico (p. 109-110) in the latter part of the 19th Century.

Well, it's been a long time since I was struck with a sudden and unforeseen disability, around 15 years ago. I was working as a nurse, a job I chose for a sense of security and safety that I lacked during my childhood. I kept hearing that people would always get sick, so I figured nursing was a safe bet. Even though my heart yearned for a career in science or journalism, the security of a consistent job was too appealing to pass up.

But life had other plans. At 46, I found myself unable to work, my body broken by an illness I never saw coming. My savings were dwindling, and after 15 long years of relying on Social Security Disability, I have little left to call my own. Every day is a struggle, a constant assault on my security and self-esteem. I am reminded daily that nothing in life is certain, yet I know I've made it this far only because of the support of my family and a few good friends. Alone, I'd be lost.

My message is clear: life is unpredictable. There will always be challenges, and no amount of preparation can shield you from everything. Sure, we should be wise and self-reliant, but the American spirit was not built on rugged individualism alone. It was built on compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. People didn't conquer the Rockies by going it alone; they did it together.

So, while I have a disaster kit and supplies, I also encourage you to build relationships with your neighbors. Trust, compassion, and mutual aid are the foundations of any strong community. Let's learn to help each other and ask for help when we need it, rather than isolating ourselves. After all, no one can go it alone forever.

Why do organisms evolve the way they do? Are there limitations or factors that influence the trajectory of evolutionary change? While D’Arcy Thompson in 1917 said, “Even now the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms,” the same can be said today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny, as seen in studies like Raup and Stanley's work in 1981. Our research explores how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, in conjunction with experimental studies, can help understand the mechanisms behind the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. Using X-radiographic images of Prunum species, we identified quantitative parameters to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies with software like CerioShell. These models help interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum, and the results are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to better grasp macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a tube that extends over time through 360 degrees of space. These turns in the shell's spiral are called whorls, which revolve around an imaginary central axis known as the columella. The rate at which whorls enlarge can vary, and each whorl is separated by a continuous line called a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl, called the body whorl, is the last one. The spire is the part of the shell without the body whorl, with the apex at the top and the base at the bottom. The animal's exit from the shell is through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed from different angles—apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural. The usual orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upwards.

To count whorls, first, view the shell from the apical side to locate the first suture, then draw a line dividing the shell. Count whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that move through time and space as the animal builds its shell. The path of the aperture can be traced using coordinates of each whorl's aperture center and the horizontal and vertical radii.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formula is established, parameters can be varied and modified to alter the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

For the past decade, Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have remained quite stable. Although the country has made progress towards many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the progress on child and maternal health indicators is lagging considerably, making it challenging to achieve the 2015 targets. The reasons for these shortcomings are multifaceted and suggest that strengthening the overall health system is a more pressing need than focusing on specific programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has seen an increase in the number of births attended by skilled healthcare workers, with 72% of births now meeting this standard. However, this figure includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions during complicated pregnancies, contributing to the high maternal mortality rate due to hemorrhage. This indicates that while progress has been made, there is still significant work to be done in this area. Additionally, there has been a decrease in the percentage of diarrhea cases in children under five years treated by a healthcare professional, and postnatal care remains a concern with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean section rates remain relatively low at around 4%, with only 2% in rural areas compared to 7% in urban areas. This highlights a severe issue of healthcare access disparity across the country, with services concentrated in urban areas. Furthermore, there is a significant gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, with a 27% difference, indicating that the poor have greater difficulty accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When considering next steps to improve neonatal and maternal health indicators, the primary question is how best to address the lack of service. Should Indonesia focus on developing program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without concentrating on pre- and post-pregnancy care? While programmatic approaches offer targeted and manageable objectives with faster results, they also come with significant drawbacks. Investing heavily in one area can lead to insufficient funding for other sectors and may result in human resources being drawn to better-resourced programs. Running multiple parallel programs without coordination can also lead to duplication of services and increased administrative burdens.

Victorian novels are known for their intricate detail and focus on the aristocracy of the era. Two notable Victorian works that break from this norm are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These novels incorporate an element of mystery and an unconventional twist, which enriches their characters and deepens our understanding of their motivations and emotions. In Oliver Twist, for instance, such elements are often revealed through dream sequences or dreamlike states. These strange occurrences often shed light on Oliver’s inner turmoil, his awareness of his surroundings, and the true nature of events around him. When Oliver revisits the shooting of himself in chapter 28, he experiences it as if in a dream, grappling to find help. The passage emphasizes Oliver’s lack of control over the unfolding events and the dire state of his health, evident through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself numbs all his senses, and he doesn’t notice the “unseen hand” that carries him away. He relives his despair removed from the initial shock of pain, now constant and linked with fear. This shooting underscores Oliver’s inability to take control of his circumstances, even when his life is at stake. It suggests a growing sense of defeat, as if Fagin has broken him, forcing him to accept his despair and influencing his ability to react. It is implied that Oliver would have made some effort to save his life had he not been overwhelmed by his circumstances.

A couple of years back, I was part of an after-school program where I tutored elementary age students. I did my best to assist them in any subjects they were struggling with, but my strengths lay in English and reading. One particular student, Adrian, needed help with reading and it quickly became apparent that something wasn't right. He could read perfectly, but he had peculiar difficulties with certain letters. It didn't make sense; he spoke perfect English, but the problem was that he didn't know the English alphabet well. One day, his mother arrived. She spoke only Spanish, and even with my limited Spanish, we managed to communicate. That's when I realized Adrian's issue; he could read, but he didn't know the English alphabet. I'm not sure if that revelation helped him, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the challenge of language barriers in schools, especially in California. It shows that even when a child speaks perfect English, reading can still be a hurdle. I believe we all agree this is an issue, so what can we do about it? For Adrian, the solution was straightforward: he needed tutoring in English reading, especially the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is more complex. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none of these alone can solve the problem. The key is to combine all these methods!

Firstly, the dual language system is a great idea, not just for Spanish-speaking children, but for all kids. Studies show that children in these programs outperform their peers academically. However, there's a lot of fear surrounding this idea, that it's a waste of resources. That's not true. If we implemented these programs in all classrooms, all children would benefit. How do we do it? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that's unrealistic. But we can certainly have bilingual aids or tutors to assist.

From the time we are kids, we're often told there's something larger than ourselves, something we can't comprehend. Some of us are taught about it in Sunday school, others in temples, or we look within ourselves for answers. Many of us just accept what our parents believed, while some reject it and believe in nothing beyond our own egocentric universe. We may adopt one value system, then change our minds later. Whatever path we choose, we define a part of ourselves through our unique spiritual perspectives. We seek a light to guide us out of the darkness and into the sun.

"Cardinals," my dad said when I asked him about his favorite bird. We were sitting on the porch, listening to the rain, smoking our cigarettes. The gutters overflowed, drowning the plants at the edge. He seemed distant, thinner, and his hair was sparse. He stared at the rain, not meeting my eyes. I felt alone, afraid, and unable to talk about how much I'd miss him. I hugged him, moved my chair closer, and watched the rain with him.

My dad passed away in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation didn't ease his suffering, but kept him alive a few months longer. I couldn't watch him leave this life. I wanted to remember him by how he lived, not how he died. I curled up and waited for the news.

No one called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, in essence, an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt puts it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has been both criticized and celebrated, accused of lacking depth and praised for its 'terrible sublime' effect (Burke). The original Gothic Novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, combined ideas from "ancient and modern" romances to establish the Gothic genre and a new mode of literary expression. Walpole used "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to create what he termed "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre incorporates numerous throwbacks to medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. When The Castle of Otranto was published, the term "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and time periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated. The blend of the more theatrical "Gothic" and the new format of the novel (allowing for a more personal view of characters' psychology) has kept Gothic relevant for centuries, making it both obsolete and fresh for readers far removed from its original period.

One prominent Gothic theme found in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, the training of a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is crucial to Gothic writers because it represents the classic knight—brave, honorable, and competent—while also highlighting their perceived lack of these qualities in contemporary society. By employing chivalric concepts and mannerisms, the "Gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, hinting at the genre's future evolution into Romanticism. Walpole, writing during a politically tumultuous period and grappling with unfair accusations, may have begun to question the morality and innate "goodness" of people, as compared to the supposed ideals of the Gothic era. This notion is evident in several characters, including Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, the reader learns that he embodies many chivalric traits. He is described as:

The description includes numerous traditionally chivalric images; Frederic is, foremost, a prince, he has suffered, been suitably affected by tragedy that he leaves, and is currently thought to have been killed by infidels. The figure of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is, of course, exaggerated, bringing into play the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Duke Ellington's impact in jazz music is largely due to his longevity and the creative prowess he brought to his orchestra. His presence on the piano, while subtle in many compositions, showcases his ability to craft rich and intricate pieces that highlight the unique talents of his band members. Ellington designed a framework that allowed for soloists to freely improvise, while also writing tightly orchestrated sections that emphasized the individual styles of his musicians, creating harmonious and original sounds for each piece. His mastery of each player's sound, along with how they blended together in a growing ensemble, allowed him to compose some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's sound and innovation, mentioning his use of voice as a jazz instrument throughout his career. This is evident in his early piece, Creole Love Call, where Ellington uses voice to add texture and color without lyrics. Here, the voice complements the styles of his soloists, a trait that persists throughout his career. This slow, twelve-bar blues piece features six choruses, each with a unique call and response between voice and reeds, showcasing Ellington's ability to create a rich tapestry of sound.

In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a complementary sound. This piece, like many of Ellington’s works, showcases his ability to blend different musical styles and instruments seamlessly. In It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing), Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's unique sound on muted trombone to great effect in introducing the melody.

Ellington’s use of voice to add a layer of tone color to his pieces is just one example of his stylistic brilliance that runs throughout his career.

She had always felt a void, a desire that remained unfulfilled. At 14, she started to crave something, and at 17, it was still there. She had figured out she wanted a person, not an object, but she couldn't find any appeal in the boys who showed interest. She questioned her strange condition, yet nothing she theorized seemed satisfactory. So, she carried on, wondering about her desires.

Peace was usually the norm at home. Her parents were calm and never argued much, except when she pushed her boundaries. They were a laid-back couple, but she balanced them with her fun-loving personality, making her quite charming.

Today, however, was different. As she wandered around, searching for inspiration, she heard her mother's scream from the kitchen. She rushed in to find her mother on the ground, hurting. "Mom! What's wrong?" she asked, panicking. Her mom was in severe pain, and she directed her daughter to take her to the hospital. The daughter, grateful for her strength training, carried her mother to the car and drove to the hospital.

The hospital was filled with the scent of disinfectant and sickness, but she was focused on helping her mother. After handing her over to the doctors, she sat worriedly, waiting for news.

Her mother had fallen off a stepladder while reaching for a high cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that sticking to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", can reduce the risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a tweaked version of the Med diet, featuring higher consumption of plant-based foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, as well as monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats) and fish, with lower intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Well, 2007 was a year when the United States of America was hit by a severe financial crisis. Unemployment soared, the housing market collapsed, and many of the nation's major corporations were left in shambles. This economic downturn is still ongoing today, so we must ask: how did this crisis come about, and how can we prevent it from happening again? In essence, the financial crisis was caused by self-centered and naive political decisions that pushed banks and firms to offer sub-prime loans, which were sold to an immature and underdeveloped financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to back and package these mortgages into CDOs and CDS'. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks found themselves short on capital reserves and transferred this turmoil to the repacked mortgages they had sold, and eventually to the rest of the economy.

The origins of this financial crisis can be traced back to 1999 during the Clinton administration. The President was aiming for a second term and sought to boost his popularity, which led to the relaxation of lending restrictions. This paved the way for the sub-prime crisis just seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times in 1999 reported, "Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest mortgage underwriter, faced increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans to low and moderate-income people, while also feeling pressure from shareholders to maintain its remarkable growth in profits." Holmes accurately predicted the consequences of these actions: "However, the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, necessitating a government rescue similar to that of the Savings and Loan industry in the 1980s." As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foretold, imprudent lending would indeed lead to the economy’s collapse.

Several factors combined to push the economy into a tailspin, with one being the complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and CDOs were widely used in the years before the crisis, further intertwining various economic sectors with the housing market. This overleveraged the U.S. households and financial markets in the housing sector, leaving them highly susceptible to even minor price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were severely impacted. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, which represented about 30% of the USA's GDP. Eventually, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at bargain prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to stringent regulation. Fannie and Freddie, with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That part of your tale where you flex your writer's muscles and soar, dazzling your readers with your enchanting prose. Or the section where your audience nods off and hits the "Back" button, cursing your name. Dr. Merlin herself has caught herself shouting at her screen when she's wading through Too Much Information, and not in the interesting way.

Exposition is not your ally.

My gentle readers already know the writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still finds herself tripping over long passages where nothing substantial occurs, or worse, too much detail. Exposition is that little imp on your shoulder telling you to rush through the history to get to the good stuff (not to be confused with the imp on the other shoulder pushing to tell your audience every last detail of your characters' backstories).

Exposition means laying out what happened, typically in straightforward language. In film, the exposition happens when one character shares a laundry list of information with another, like "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the sharing.

Consider this: while reading a story, you're told something like, "The heroine met her beloved at such a time and place, they were wed in a grand event, and he was murdered in front of her eyes." You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to consume two pages, during which both characters exchange only a couple of lines. You'd expect the author to spend time on the husband's character, revealing through his dialogue and actions how deeply he loved his wife, and you'd likewise expect the heroine to show through both big and small ways how his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story later says her love was profound). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to feel his loss as she does and would give you insight into the heroine's life: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as seen through his eyes, and so on. You'd mourn his death with her, and so grow more invested in the heroine herself.

In essence, you need to provide the substance that brings the story to life. Sometimes it's tempting to hurry through certain aspects. Maybe you're introducing a new character and you know he was in the Air Force, is the night manager of a gas station now, divorced twice, no kids, loves fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

Yesterday, I caught two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, aired live on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011), discussed a disturbing incident in Ashley, Ohio. The story involved a man named Shad Hostettler who had stabbed his wife; they didn't mention her name, but the mug shot they showed looked chilling. They dedicated only about two minutes to the developing story, which, I believe, was appropriate. The second story, featuring an early morning shooting in Sharon Woods, involved Travis Buyers, an 18-year-old who had been critically injured. There were no arrests at the time, and the SWAT team was investigating. This story was brief, and I suspect that might have been due to the fact that it involved a person of color. I've noticed over the years that crimes against minorities often don't receive as much attention as they deserve. The next story was about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter, which was believed to have been caused by a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest. Following that, they reported on the predicted rain and thunderstorms for Saturday afternoon, with temperatures expected to stay in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. This segment was brief, but it served as a teaser to keep viewers tuned in. They also covered a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus, where a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie sweatshirt had been involved. They devoted an unusual amount of time to emphasize his race and the fact that he was tall and weighed around 150 pounds. Lastly, they mentioned a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin named Rene Rodriguez, who had been sentenced to 300 months in prison for conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. They also noted his Hispanic background, which, in my opinion, was not relevant to the story.

The bond between brothers is a unique and unyielding connection, filled with a myriad of emotions—love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty among others. Brothers understand each other in a way no one else can, and they often see their own reflection in their sibling. This bond is most apparent in dire situations, where its true nature emerges, be it for better or worse. The emotions that form from this fraternal link come with a significant price. Understanding these emotions means also accepting the consequences they bring. When you look into your brother's eyes, you see yourself as you truly are, not as others perceive you. It is in their actions and the aftermath of those actions that their genuine character is revealed. This theme is vividly explored in “The Scarlet Ibis,” where two brothers embark on a doomed journey, navigating through a lush landscape. The story is rich with Doodle's direct characterization and his interactions with his older brother, as well as with the narrator's perspective, which provides insight into the complex emotions and actions of both characters.

The protagonist's actions are driven by a single emotion: pride. From the time he first goes out with Doodle to their final, tragic excursion, the protagonist harbors resentment towards his younger brother. He yearned for a companion he could teach all his skills, such as holding his breath, running, and climbing trees, as well as someone to race with and perch with in the tallest pine. However, Doodle's frail heart made it unlikely he would ever participate in such activities. This placed a heavy burden on the protagonist, whose dreams were dashed in an instant. This realization even led him to contemplate harming Doodle, illustrating the depth of his resentment. Yet, his heart softened when Doodle simply smiled at him, showing that his initial intentions were not truly evil. The smile gave the protagonist hope, highlighting his underlying love for his brother, despite his initial resentment.

The human brain, an intricate and imaginative information processor, has seen its metaphors evolve with technological progress. From a wax tablet to a computer, these metaphors help us understand the brain but can also lead to misconceptions. Information begins as sensory inputs, transforming physical stimuli like touch, warmth, sound waves, or light into electrochemical signals. These signals are processed through algorithms, both bottom-up and top-down. For instance, when you see a black box on white paper, bottom-up processing combines simple details like color and edge borders to recognize it as a box. Top-down processing then speeds up your recognition by using prior decisions. The brain's attention filter sorts information's importance, deciding which cognitive processes to prioritize. For example, while walking, you might notice your name in a noisy room, ignoring individual blades of grass. This processing involves multiple stages, modulated by attention.

Information storage is crucial for the brain. There are various types of memory, such as sensory, working, and long-term. Encoding involves converting sensory inputs into different types of information, like structural, phonetic, or semantic. Working memory, with a brief storage period, is maintained by electrical signals looping through specific neurons. Long-term memory is believed to rely on specific protein structures. Multiple models organize knowledge in the brain, ranging from human memory retrieval to computer science and neurophysiology. The semantic network model proposes nodes representing concepts linked by their relatedness, such as "chair" linked to "table" and "wooden"

Aldous Huxley voices concern over the looming threat of technology and capitalistic systems, creating a dystopian society in Brave New World. The citizenry prioritizes community over individualism and is conditioned from birth to chase happiness at all costs. They are pawns in a larger scheme controlled by the World Controller, who dictates their ideology. Examining the novel through a Marxist lens reveals Huxley's skepticism about these emerging systems, using terms like homogenization and reification to highlight its flaws.

Capitalism is critiqued through the concept of false consciousness. The common folks are kept unaware of their true economic relations, focusing instead on self-interest. This is achieved through the proletariat's ideological control, evident in Brave New World's conditioning. The common classes, such as Deltas and Gammas, lack free will and are driven to consume and indulge. This manipulation is orchestrated by the World Controller. Hegemony, where social classes are dominated by a separate group, is clear. The lower classes are unaware of manipulation, being "sold on an ideology that upholds the structure" (capitalism and consumerism). Even the upper classes, like Alphas and Betas, accept their status, with few exceptions like Bernard. The societal interactions reveal the oppression of capitalism.

In Brave New World, relationships are shallow. Characters lack depth, even among major figures. Huxley might suggest that technology and capitalism rob individuals of free will and expression. Love doesn't exist, nor intense emotions; interactions are superficial. Males comment on females' physical appearance, and females discuss their encounters casually. Each societal class' complacency with their role indicates capitalism's socioeconomic effects. Their unquestioning obedience signifies Marxist thought, where the proletariat are made to believe they are superior as long as they consume and adhere to their peers.

Well, I've been hanging out at University Park for nearly two and a half years now, which adds up to four semesters. Navigating the campus can be a real pain, especially for freshmen. My first year, I was stuck in an East Halls dorm room, pretty much at the farthest point east on campus. Just getting to classes in places like Willard building could take up to 25 minutes on foot, and that's not counting the bad weather we usually get in State College. Turns out, not too long ago, East Halls were isolated from the rest of the campus by vast empty spaces. Now, those have been filled with sports fields, new buildings like the Creamery and health services center, and apartments. As campus keeps growing, it's getting harder to get around. So, what's the best solution to the campus commute conundrum? Bikes are the way to go.

My buddy just started riding again after a long break, and he's loving it. “Bikes are awesome,” he says, “they're the only way to get around.” Besides being good for your body, they're the most efficient mode of transport. A bowl of oats and a little workout can cover 30 miles no problem. I, too, live off campus, about as far from the center as some dorms. The smartest decision I made this year was getting a bike. Thomas building, where I have class every day, is a 25-minute walk from my place. On my bike, that time cuts to 5 minutes. The only downside is Pollock Road, the fastest route to Thomas, isn't always a smooth ride. Still, walking takes too much time, especially when you're as busy as I am. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option. Walking to Thomas would add 30-40 minutes each day, and that's over two and a half hours a week. Let's not forget the extra time for other classes, appointments, and so on. That's a lot of time I can't spare.
